  "slug": "tea-loaf",
  "title": "Tea loaf",
  "subtitle": "Fruit soaked in cold tea, baked in a loaf tin",
  "excerpt": "Tea loaf is made by soaking dried fruit overnight in cold strong black tea, then binding it with egg and flour the next day. There is no fat in the recipe, the tea-plumped fruit provides all the moisture. It keeps for a week and improves as it sits.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Tea loaf appears across Welsh, Yorkshire, and Scottish regional cooking under various names: bara brith (Welsh), Yorkshire tea loaf, and Scots black bun share the same technique of soaking dried fruit in liquid before baking. Mrs Beeton, Book of Household Management (1861), Project Gutenberg #10136, tea-soaked fruit cakes appear in the bread and cake chapters as a standard British domestic form.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Tea loaf requires a ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "tea soak",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpb836pt000020v407m9br3z"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " that starts the night before, the fruit must soak for at least 6 hours, overnight is better. The longer it soaks, the more liquid it absorbs, and the moister the finished loaf. The actual mixing takes about 5 minutes the next morning.",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "infoPanel",
        "attrs": {
          "type": "note"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "text": "Brew two strong cups of black tea, leave to cool completely, then pour over the fruit. The cold temperature is deliberate, hot tea starts to cook the fruit and makes the soaking less effective. Any plain black tea works; builder's tea is fine.",
                "type": "text"
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
